title: For Sale:  Scam Alert please flag em
postcontent: This add repeatedly appears on the Colorado Armslist. Number one if that TRP was really for sale at that price it would have been gone three months ago at that price. Please flag that ad before he scams someone else. title: For Sale:  Colt 1911 Display Training Model [1944]
postcontent:
COLT 1911 DISPLAY TRAINING MODEL

Description:
 Measuring 32 inches tall, 50 inches long and 8 inches wide, this is a large scale model of a Colt Model 1911A1 Semi-Automatic Pistol. The slide is mobile, with the hammer spring loaded to move out of the way, a mobile slide catch and a function magazine catch, which when depressed releases a scale model magazine. A length of pipe extends down from the trigger guard, with two reinforcing sections on the front strap for mounting the display on the included floor stand. Also included is a black painted hardwood transport case. This
was made by a unknown Company in 1944-1946. There were  six [6] total producted,
this is the only one know in existance.
According to a notarized affidavit from a previous owner, this was used as a training aid by the U.S. Navy to train Naval Aviators and eventually became part of the inventory of Patrick Air Force Base (formerly Naval Air Station Banana River) in Florida, and the slide markings were added when it was disposed of by the Air Force. 
Condition: Excellent, with a few mild handling marks overall. The magazine shows a pair of deep cuts in the left side. This is an absolute must for the serious 45 automatic collector!

In development for more than four years, the VP9 is Heckler & Kochâs latest handgun and the first striker fired HK since the renowned P7 series pistols were introduced in the 1980s.

Experience gained by HK engineers with the recent P30 pistol had a direct influence on the design of the VP9, but the VP9 breaks new ground with its integration of a unique striker firing system with an enhanced HK âlight pullâ trigger. The net result is trigger quality unequaled in any production striker fired handgun.

HK pioneered the first striker fired handguns, producing both the VP70 and P7 series, designs that impacted several models by HK competitors. But a superior trigger has eluded most striker fired pistol designs. The VP9 trigger surpasses those found on competitors. It has a short, light take-up with a solid, single action type break followed by a short positive reset.

The VP9 trigger has a consistent pre-travel pull with a positive wall/crisp break. Typically, striker fired guns have a pre-travel pull that increases in weight as you go through the trigger stroke. With the VP9, you have a less than noticeable pre-travel pull until the trigger reaches the engagement point of the fire control parts prior to trigger break.

The VP9 uses HKâs ergonomic handgun grip design that includes three changeable backstraps and six side panelsâ accommodating all hand sizes. Molded finger grooves in the front of the pistolâs grip also instinctively position an operatorâs hand for optimal shooting. Only HK handguns have such a customized grip.

Although influenced by other HK models, the VP9 has all the hallmarks of the latest, state-of-the-art handgun. All controls are completely ambidextrous. Slide releases are present on both sides of the frame and the magazine release can be easily activated by left- or right-handed shooters.

A new feature is HKâs patented charging supports â simple components that are mounted on each side of the rear of the slide and provide better gripping leverage for racking the slide rearward. The charging supports speed reloading and make operating the VP9 easier for shooters with reduced hand strength. The VP pistols uses the proven P30 steel magazine; 15 and 10-round capacity available.

The VP9 has an extended Picatinny MIL-STD-1913 rail molded into its polymer frame for mounting lights and accessories. The rail has been tested and certified to handle mounted accessories up to 5.6 ounces.

The VP9âs proprietary captive flat recoil spring helps reduce the recoil forces effecting the operator and the handgun, improving shooter control during rapid firing and prolonging component service life.

HKâs famous cold hammer forged barrel â made from cannon grade steel â ensures long service life. Similar HK barrels on 9 mm P30 models have fired more than 90,000 rounds in endurance tests in 2010. The polygonal bore profile, with no traditional lands-and-grooves rifling, contributes to longer service life as well as a slight increase in muzzle velocity.

The VP9âs machined steel slide is protected from corrosion and wear by HKâs hostile environment finish and all metal components, including springs and pins have superior metallurgy.

VP pistols are made in Heckler & Kochâs Oberndorf factory in southwest Germany. The VP9 is well-suited for civilian sport shooting, security, military, and law enforcement use.

Covered by Heckler & Kochâs limited lifetime warranty, the HK VP9 is a solid design engineered with the famous long-term durability that make HK products especially cost-effective when subjected to total life cycle cost analysis. Suggested retail price of the VP9 is $719 with projected availability of July 2014.

title: For Trade:  SCAM ALERT "The Tradesman Firearms"
postcontent:
Be aware there is a very elaberate SCAM going on. Someone is advertising as a dealer. They will send you to their website www.thetradesmenfirearms.com and give you their contact information. The website is a real website and the Tradesman is a real store. 

However, this guy copied the real Tradesman website EXACTLY and changed only the contact information to his so he can take your money posing as the store. The scammers website is www.thetradesmenfirearms.com and the real stores website is www.625guns.com. Look at the real website contact information and contact them if you considering buying from this store.

title: For Sale:  2 Martini-Henry rifles from the 1880's
location: Northern Colorado Springs, Colorado Springs, Colorado
postcontent:
The Gahendra is sold only the Francotte is left (bottom gun in pics) WTS Martini Henry rifle from the 1880's  Shiny bore with lots some wear on the rifling. Still needs more cleaning.  Cash only no trades please. The forstock on the Francotte does have a piece missing as picture shows. 
I guess I'm never gonna restore these beauties so they are up for sale. Neither of the actions open up all the way (partial only). I never tried to disassemble, I don't build ar's or ak's about all I can do to disasemble my pistols. These are C&R so no FFL needed. FTF in the Springs $245 each. Top picture is the Gahendra lower is the Francotte. Martini-Henry Gahendra was based on an 1869 Westley Richards patented design, this unique and extremely rare early breechloading Military Rifle 577/450 Martini-Henry calibre was produced under the direction of General Gahendra Rana in the 1880's to provide Ghurka regiments with what appeared to be the latest British Military Rifle. An ingenious design, it really surpassed the standard Martini in that its entire action was removable as one unit for ease of servicing or exchange. Production however caused massive logistic problems and by 1894 the Ghurkas were dangerously short of viable .450 cal. breechloaders to face ever growing threats from the east. Finally the British came to the rescue with a delivery of several thousand Martini short lever rifles in late 1894 and even more long lever Martini Rifles in 1908. The over complicated Gahendra Rifle was thereafter basically shelved, the void in up-to-date arms having been met. Always considered the rarest Martini variety of all, the Gahendra Rifle has a characteristic loading lever but in other respects closely resembles the standard Martini externally. A chance to obtain an extremely rare historical antique rifle that was a close relative of one of the most successful rifle systems of all time for an UNBEATABLE price!

The Martini Francotte patent System was developed in 1878 and utilizes a detachable mechanism fitted without the Cocking Indicator. Revolutionary at the time by compartmentalizing the mechanism for quick disassembly, it only lasted 10 years as the latest technology. It was replaced in 1888 by the .303 cal Lee Metford bolt-action Rifle's introduction into the British Military System. Although the British never embraced this European improvement, these "Improved System Rifles" saw much service on frontiers all over the World. Call or text mike 719/964/zero four 71
